            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
                <p>We have a partially preserved personal name [--]ρομανδριο[- -], a compound one, where 
                    the second stem was mandr-. An exact match for our name does not seem to be attested in LGPN. 
                    There is, however, another comopound theophoric name with the stem mandr- known from Borysthenes:
                Athenomandros ( ). By analogy with that, the first stem in our case may have been also a theonym, for example,
                Ietros.  Compound personal names with mandr- as the second of the two stems are common in Ionia.</p>
                <p>The grammatical case of the personal name on our cup may have been either Nominative, in which case 
                the inscription could be dedicatory, or Genitive, in which case we would have an ownership inscription. 
                The Nominative case would leave the possibility of an ownership inscription as well.</p>
            </div>
